            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Scott Miller\u2019s story is one of tangible things in an increasingly digital world. Raised in a middle-class Portland, Oregon, family, his childhood was spent in his father\u2019s meticulously organized garage. While his mother, a high school librarian, fostered a love for books, it was his father, a union machinist, who taught him the profound satisfaction of making something work with his own hands. This practical upbringing led him straight to Oregon State University for a degree in Mechanical Engineering.\n\nHe arrived in San Francisco in the late 1990s, drawn by the magnetic pull of the dot-com boom. His first job was a trial by fire at a hardware startup that burned bright and fast, ultimately imploding but teaching him invaluable lessons about rapid iteration and resilience. The long hours also cost him his first marriage, a painful turning point that solidified his resolve to find more balance in his life. Scott methodically rebuilt his career, earning a reputation not as a flashy visionary, but as the indispensable engineer who could turn ambitious concepts into functional, elegant prototypes. This reputation carried him up the ladder to his current Director role.\n\nToday, Scott lives in a quiet Potrero Hill apartment with views of the downtown skyline he helps shape. His daily 3.5-mile bike commute to his SoMa lab is a non-negotiable ritual, a time to observe the city\u2019s physical mechanics. He\u2019s in a committed relationship with Chloe, an urban planner whose work complements his own fascination with how physical spaces function.\n\nWhile he enjoys his professional success, Scott feels a pull back to his roots. His dream isn\u2019t a C-suite position but a smaller, independent workshop. He envisions a future where he can step away from managing PowerPoints and return to the hum of a lathe, building bespoke furniture or consulting for smaller creators. He wants to end his career as he started it: with grease on his hands and the quiet pride of having built something real and lasting."
